{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18692"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76854"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10168"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26463"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76854"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERuffini corpuscles are specialised sensory receptors found in human skin and joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of Ruffini corpuscles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sense light touch","Detect sustained skin stretch","Detect temperature changes","Respond to vibration","Identify sharp pressure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of Ruffini corpuscles is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edetect sustained skin stretch\u003C/strong\u003E. These slow-adapting mechanoreceptors are located in the deep dermis of the skin and in joint capsules. They continue to fire action potentials throughout a maintained stretch stimulus, making them crucial for monitoring joint position and movement.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESense light touch\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily detected by Meissner corpuscles in the superficial dermis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespond to vibration\u003C/strong\u003E - Pacinian corpuscles are specialised for detecting vibration and rapid pressure changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetect temperature changes\u003C/strong\u003E - Temperature is detected by thermoreceptors, not mechanoreceptors like Ruffini corpuscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdentify sharp pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Sharp pressure is detected by free nerve endings and other rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe slow-adapting nature of Ruffini corpuscles makes them particularly suited for providing continuous feedback about skin stretch and joint position.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ruffini corpuscles are slow-adapting mechanoreceptors that detect skin stretch and joint movement.","Ruffini corpuscles are located in the deep layers of the skin and joint capsules.","As slow-adapting receptors, Ruffini corpuscles continue to fire throughout sustained stimulation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62359"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMe